    "summary": "The First Chechen War (1994–1996) was a catastrophic military failure for Russia as it attempted to suppress the independence of the small Caucasian republic of Chechnya. The Chechen government under Dzhokhar Dudayev had declared independence following the Soviet collapse, and Yeltsin's government decided to use force to prevent secession and discourage other independence movements within the Russian Federation. Russian forces invaded in December 1994, expecting a quick victory.\n\nInstead, they encountered fierce urban guerrilla resistance that revealed catastrophic deficiencies in Russia's post-Soviet military. The assault on Grozny in January 1995 was a disaster: hundreds of Russian soldiers died in burning armored vehicles in street fighting against Chechen fighters who knew the city intimately. The war dragged on at enormous human cost — approximately 5,000 to 14,000 Russian soldiers and tens of thousands of Chechen civilians killed — and was widely unpopular within Russia. The Khasavyurt Accords of August 1996 ended the first war with a de facto Chechen victory: Russian forces withdrew and Chechnya operated as a virtually independent state until the [[event:2776|Second Chechen War]] began in 1999.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Chechen_War",
